What is Spring Boot?

Spring Boot is a Java framework used to build backend applications quickly.

Think of it like this:

Java = The programming language.
Spring = A powerful framework that provides tools for building enterprise applications.
Spring Boot = A simplified version of Spring that removes much of the setup and configuration, so you can start building faster.
Real-world analogy

Imagine you want to build a house.

Java gives you the bricks.
Spring gives you the architecture and construction tools.
Spring Boot gives you a nearly ready-to-build house where most of the plumbing and wiring are already set up.

So instead of spending days configuring everything, you focus on building your application's features.

What do companies build with Spring Boot?

A backend handles things like:

User login
Storing user data
Processing payments
Managing orders
Serving APIs to mobile apps and websites

For example, when you open a food delivery app:

You click Order.
The app sends a request to the backend.
A Spring Boot application:
Checks if you're logged in.
Verifies the restaurant.
Saves the order to the database.
Sends back a confirmation.
How Spring Boot works
Mobile App / Website
          │
          ▼
      Spring Boot
          │
          ▼
       SQL Database

The frontend talks to the Spring Boot backend, and the backend talks to the database.

Example

Suppose you have a website that stores students.

A user visits:

GET /students

Spring Boot receives the request.

Your Java code might look like:

@GetMapping("/students")
public List<Student> getStudents() {
    return studentService.getAllStudents();
}

Spring Boot then:

Runs this method.
Gets the students from the database.
Returns them as JSON.

Example response:

[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "name": "Ishan"
  },
  {
    "id": 2,
    "name": "Rahul"
  }
]
Why do companies like Spring Boot?
Very fast to develop with.
Reliable for large-scale applications.
Easy to connect with databases like MySQL and PostgreSQL.
Large ecosystem and community.
Common choice for enterprise software.

Many banks, e-commerce platforms, and enterprise companies use it because it's mature and scalable.
